{"title_page": "Lauren Hoffman", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Lauren Hoffman\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1977}}\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], [[U.S.]]\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[Piano]], [[Synth]], [[Synth]], [[Bass (guitar)|Bass]], [[Tambourine]], [[Guitar]]\n| genre            = [[Acoustic music|Acoustic]]<br/>[[Folk music|Folk]]<br/>[[Alternative rock]]<br/>[[Lo-fi music|Lo-fi]]<br/>[[Pop music|Pop]]<br/>[[Independent music|Indie]]\n| occupation       = [[Singer-Songwriter]]\n| years_active     = \n| label            = [[Virgin Records]]<br/>{{Interlanguage link|Fargo Records|fr||WD=}}<br/>[[Slow River Records]]<br/>[[PIAS Recordings]]<br/>[[Kill Rock Stars]]<br/>Free Union Records<br/>Dreamy Records<br/>Pitch-a-Tent Records\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.laurenhoffman.com/}}\n| associated_acts  = [[Mirabai]]<br/>[[Lilith Fair]]\n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = \n}}\n\n'''Lauren Hoffman''' is an American [[singer-songwriter]]. She released her debut album ''[[Megiddo (Lauren Hoffman album)|Megiddo]]'' through [[Virgin Records]] in 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forlauren.com|title=ForLauren.com}}</ref> to critical praise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/megiddo-mw0000023092|title=Megiddo - Lauren Hoffman {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/03/movies/pop-and-jazz-guide-413100.html|title=Pop and Jazz Guide|date=1997-10-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-12-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eggEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=lauren+hoffman+megiddo+review+1997&source=bl&ots=MW9TN2R8m3&sig=Fgn5vsZ3G6kik2h0OaEl9PH6tss&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjv3OWY28jfAhUh2oMKHbKDAuo4FBDoATAJegQIABAB#v=onepage&q=lauren%20hoffman%20megiddo%20review%201997&f=false|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1999-11-06|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> In 1999 Hoffman issued her second LP ''From The Blue House'', and an EP entitled ''A Harmless Little Kiss;''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Lauren-Hoffman-A-Harmless-Little-Kiss-EP/release/670843|title=A Harmless Little Kiss}}</ref> both were independently released through her record label, Free Union Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/lauren-hoffman-mn0000117238|title=Artist Biography by Stacia Proefrock}}</ref> Her third album ''[[Choreography (Lauren Hoffman album)|Choreography]] was'' released through a [[France|French]] record label named Fargo Records in 2006, which includes her successful single \"Broken.\" In 2015 Hoffman released two EPs under new moniker, The Secret Storm: ''In the Sun''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soundhound.com/?ar=200901548495050519|title=The Secret Storm}}</ref> and ''The Dragon.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ghettoblastermagazine.com/lauren-hoffman-the-secret-storm-on-the-dragon-ep/|title=The Dragon}}</ref> Her fourth full-length album ''Family Ghost'' arrived in 2017.\n\n==Biography==\nHoffman was born in Los Angeles, in 1977. She moved to Charlottesville, Virginia, at the age of 2.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.c-ville.com/little-bit-fixed-lauren-hoffman-shifts-back-local-spotlight/|title=Little bit fixed: Lauren Hoffman|last=|first=|date=2015-03-31|work=C-VILLE Weekly|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> She played bass with [[Shannon Worrell]] and [[September '67|Kristin Asbury]] in a band called Monsoon, named after the Thai restaurant in which they played.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailyprogress.com/entertainment/globetrotter-lauren-hoffman-owns-the-spotlight/article_d78d74b6-01b3-11e6-bcad-1fe5eb6087dc.html|title=Globetrotter Lauren Hoffman|last=|first=|date=|work=The Daily Progress|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en}}</ref> She later left the band to focus on her own work. Hoffman released her first full length album ''[[Megiddo (Lauren Hoffman album)|Megiddo]]'' when she was 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soundhound.com/?ar=200901548495050519|title=The Secret Storm: A Biography by Marcy Donelson|last=|first=|date=|website=SoundHound|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> She parted ways with Virgin Records taking her full rights of the album \u2014 as it was poorly promoted. ''Megiddo'' was produced with John Morand and David Lowery; the album was mixed by Ethan Johns<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ethan-johns-mn0000171535/credits|title=Artist Ethan Johns}}</ref> and recorded at the Sound of Music studio in Richmond. During her early career, she was artistically inspired  by [[Jeff Buckley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.girlieaction.com/lauren-hoffman-and-the-secret-storm/|title=Girlie Action|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n\nHoffman produced her second album ''From The Blue House,'' which was released in 1999. Her major was Dance Choreography at Virginia Commonwealth University \u2014 which inspired the name of her third album, ''[[Choreography (Lauren Hoffman album)|Choreography]]''. She left VCU in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://home.btconnect.com/PlumPromotions/bands/laurenhoffman.htm|title=PlumPromotions: Bands}}</ref> Throughout her travel experiences she eventually recorded ''The Lucknow Demos.'' These recordings also partly inspirited her 2006 album ''Choreography,'' preceded by the release of her fourth album ''Interplanetary Traveler''. She recorded this album in a studio in Israel; it was released in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.popmatters.com/120740-lauren-hoffman-interplanetary-traveler-2496165336.html|title=Lauren Hoffman: Interplanetary Traveler|date=2010-03-01|work=PopMatters|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en}}</ref> Hoffman and her friends later formed a band in Charlottesville: The Secret Storm. After their first two EP', they released ''Family Ghost'' in 2017 under a new name: Lauren Hoffman & The Secret Storm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soundhound.com/?ar=200901548495050519|title=Lauren Hoffman & The Secret Storm|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> She released several of her EPs and albums in both Europe and America on 7\" and 12\" vinyl and CD.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n* ''[[Megiddo (Lauren Hoffman album)|Megiddo]] (1997)''\n* ''From The Blue House (1999)''\n* ''[[Choreography (Lauren Hoffman album)|Choreography]] (2006)''\n* ''Interplanetary Traveler (2010)''\n* ''Lauren Hoffman & The Secret Storm: Family Ghost (2017)''\n*''Mercury Girls (2019)''\n\n===Singles & EPs===\n* ''Fall Away (1996) 7\" Vinyl''\n* ''The Chemist Said It Would Be Alright But I\u2019ve Never Been The Same (1997)''\n* ''Rock Star (1997) 12\" Vinyl''\n* ''Lolita (1997) 12\" Vinyl''\n* ''A Harmless Little Kiss (1999)''\n* ''Song For A Boy (2000) 7\" Vinyl''\n* ''Solipsist (2006) Single''\n* ''The Secret Storm: In The Sun (2015)''  \n* ''The Secret Storm: The Dragon (2015)''\n* ''Lauren Hoffman & The Secret Storm: A Friend for the Apocalypse (2017) Single''\n*''Shadow of the Moon (2018) Single''\n*''Heartbreak and Tacos (2019) Single''\n\n=== ''Hallmark Releases'' ===\n\n* ''The Lucknow Demos (2003) [Available to public 2018]''\n* ''Megiddo - 20th Anniversary All-Analog Vinyl Reissue (2018)''\n\n==Arts and Filmography==\nAfter her album Megiddo was released in 1997, Hoffman spent some time traveling India, Europe and Israel to tour and forego her musical endeavour. She later studied the art of dance and choreography at Virginia Commonwealth University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.readthehook.com/93971/facetime-girl-interrupted-hoffman-i-was-just-too-young|title=The Hook: Girl interrupted|last=|first=|date=|website=readthehook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> In 2002 she decided to move forward from her study of dance to pursue her passion of music, while also incorporating her talent as a dancer; with her fellow peers, she went on to produce several musical and dance video productions for some her songs, including ''Solipsist'' and ''Another Song About the Darkness.'' (''Choreography'' 2006).   \n\nThe album cover for her EP ''The Chemist Said It Would Be Alright But I\u2019ve Never Been The Same,'' was designed by [[outsider artist]] [[Wes Freed]]. ''Another Song About the Darkness'', from her album ''[[Choreography (Lauren Hoffman album)|Choreography]]'', is included on [[The Sound the Hare Heard]] album. A number of Hoffman's songs were played in the groundbreaking LGBT series [[South of Nowhere]], including ''Ghost You Know'', ''Magic Stick'', ''Hope You Don't Mind'', ''Reasons to Fall'' and ''Broken''. Her song ''Rock Star'' appears on the soundtrack of the 1998 motion picture, ''[[Palmetto (film)|Palmetto]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.laurenhoffman.com laurenhoffman.com]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoffman, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American folk singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Lauren Hoffman\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1977}}\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], [[U.S.]]\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[Piano]], [[Synth]], [[Synth]], [[Bass (guitar)|Bass]], [[Tambourine]], [[Guitar]]\n| genre            = [[Acoustic music|Acoustic]]<br/>[[Folk music|Folk]]<br/>[[Alternative rock]]<br/>[[Lo-fi music|Lo-fi]]<br/>[[Pop music|Pop]]<br/>[[Independent music|Indie]]\n| occupation       = [[Singer-Songwriter]]\n| years_active     = \n| label            = [[Virgin Records]]<br/>{{Interlanguage link|Fargo Records|fr||WD=}}<br/>[[Slow River Records]]<br/>[[PIAS Recordings]]<br/>[[Kill Rock Stars]]<br/>Free Union Records<br/>Dreamy Records<br/>Pitch-a-Tent Records\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.laurenhoffman.com/}}\n| associated_acts  = [[Mirabai]]<br/>[[Lilith Fair]]\n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = \n}}\n\n'''Lauren Hoffman''' is an American [[singer-songwriter]]. She released her debut album ''[[Megiddo (Lauren Hoffman album)|Megiddo]]'' through [[Virgin Records]] in 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forlauren.com|title=ForLauren.com}}</ref> to critical praise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/megiddo-mw0000023092|title=Megiddo - Lauren Hoffman {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/03/movies/pop-and-jazz-guide-413100.html|title=Pop and Jazz Guide|date=1997-10-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-12-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eggEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=lauren+hoffman+megiddo+review+1997&source=bl&ots=MW9TN2R8m3&sig=Fgn5vsZ3G6kik2h0OaEl9PH6tss&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjv3OWY28jfAhUh2oMKHbKDAuo4FBDoATAJegQIABAB#v=onepage&q=lauren%20hoffman%20megiddo%20review%201997&f=false|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1999-11-06|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> In 1999 Hoffman issued her second LP ''From The Blue House'', and an EP entitled ''A Harmless Little Kiss;''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Lauren-Hoffman-A-Harmless-Little-Kiss-EP/release/670843|title=A Harmless Little Kiss}}</ref> both were independently released through her record label, Free Union Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/lauren-hoffman-mn0000117238|title=Artist Biography by Stacia Proefrock}}</ref> Her third album ''[[Choreography (Lauren Hoffman album)|Choreography]] was'' released through a [[France|French]] record label named Fargo Records in 2006, which includes her successful single \"Broken.\" In 2015 Hoffman released two EPs under new moniker, The Secret Storm: ''In the Sun''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soundhound.com/?ar=200901548495050519|title=The Secret Storm}}</ref> and ''The Dragon.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ghettoblastermagazine.com/lauren-hoffman-the-secret-storm-on-the-dragon-ep/|title=The Dragon}}</ref> Her fourth full-length album ''Family Ghost'' arrived in 2017.\n\n==Biography==\nHoffman was born in Los Angeles, in 1977. She moved to Charlottesville, Virginia, at the age of 2.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.c-ville.com/little-bit-fixed-lauren-hoffman-shifts-back-local-spotlight/|title=Little bit fixed: Lauren Hoffman|last=|first=|date=2015-03-31|work=C-VILLE Weekly|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> She played bass with [[Shannon Worrell]] and [[September '67|Kristin Asbury]] in a band called Monsoon, named after the Thai restaurant in which they played.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailyprogress.com/entertainment/globetrotter-lauren-hoffman-owns-the-spotlight/article_d78d74b6-01b3-11e6-bcad-1fe5eb6087dc.html|title=Globetrotter Lauren Hoffman|last=|first=|date=|work=The Daily Progress|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en}}</ref> She later left the band to focus on her own work. Hoffman released her first full length album ''[[Megiddo (Lauren Hoffman album)|Megiddo]]'' when she was 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soundhound.com/?ar=200901548495050519|title=The Secret Storm: A Biography by Marcy Donelson|last=|first=|date=|website=SoundHound|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> She parted ways with Virgin Records taking her full rights of the album \u2014 as it was poorly promoted. ''Megiddo'' was produced with John Morand and David Lowery; the album was mixed by Ethan Johns<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ethan-johns-mn0000171535/credits|title=Artist Ethan Johns}}</ref> and recorded at the Sound of Music studio in Richmond. During her early career, she was artistically inspired  by [[Jeff Buckley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.girlieaction.com/lauren-hoffman-and-the-secret-storm/|title=Girlie Action|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n\nHoffman produced her second album ''From The Blue House,'' which was released in 1999. Her major was Dance Choreography at Virginia Commonwealth University \u2014 which inspired the name of her third album, ''[[Choreography (Lauren Hoffman album)|Choreography]]''. She left VCU in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://home.btconnect.com/PlumPromotions/bands/laurenhoffman.htm|title=PlumPromotions: Bands}}</ref> Throughout her travel experiences she eventually recorded ''The Lucknow Demos.'' These recordings also partly inspirited her 2006 album ''Choreography,'' preceded by the release of her fourth album ''Interplanetary Traveler''. She recorded this album in a studio in Israel; it was released in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.popmatters.com/120740-lauren-hoffman-interplanetary-traveler-2496165336.html|title=Lauren Hoffman: Interplanetary Traveler|date=2010-03-01|work=PopMatters|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en}}</ref> Hoffman and her friends later formed a band in Charlottesville: The Secret Storm. After their first two EP', they released ''Family Ghost'' in 2017 under a new name: Lauren Hoffman & The Secret Storm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soundhound.com/?ar=200901548495050519|title=Lauren Hoffman & The Secret Storm|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> She released several of her EPs and albums in both Europe and America on 7\" and 12\" vinyl and CD.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n* ''[[Megiddo (Lauren Hoffman album)|Megiddo]] (1997)''\n* ''From The Blue House (1999)''\n* ''[[Choreography (Lauren Hoffman album)|Choreography]] (2006)''\n* ''Interplanetary Traveler (2010)''\n* ''Lauren Hoffman & The Secret Storm: Family Ghost (2017)''\n*''Mercury Girls (2019)''\n\n===Singles & EPs===\n* ''Fall Away (1996) 7\" Vinyl''\n* ''The Chemist Said It Would Be Alright But I\u2019ve Never Been The Same (1997)''\n* ''Rock Star (1997) 12\" Vinyl''\n* ''Lolita (1997) 12\" Vinyl''\n* ''A Harmless Little Kiss (1999)''\n* ''Song For A Boy (2000) 7\" Vinyl''\n* ''Solipsist (2006) Single''\n* ''The Secret Storm: In The Sun (2015)''  \n* ''The Secret Storm: The Dragon (2015)''\n* ''Lauren Hoffman & The Secret Storm: A Friend for the Apocalypse (2017) Single''\n*''Shadow of the Moon (2018) Single''\n*''Heartbreak and Tacos (2019) Single''\n\n=== ''Hallmark Releases'' ===\n\n* ''The Lucknow Demos (2003) [Available to public 2018]''\n* ''Megiddo - 20th Anniversary All-Analog Vinyl Reissue (2018)''\n\n==Arts and Filmography==\nAfter her album Megiddo was released in 1997, Hoffman spent some time traveling India, Europe and Israel to tour and forego her musical endeavour. She later studied the art of dance and choreography at Virginia Commonwealth University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.readthehook.com/93971/facetime-girl-interrupted-hoffman-i-was-just-too-young|title=The Hook: Girl interrupted|last=Parsons|first=Laura|date=9\u201311\u20132003|website=https://www.readthehook.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020\u201304\u201321}}</ref> In 2002 she decided to move forward from her study of dance to pursue her passion of music, while also incorporating her talent as a dancer; with her fellow peers, she went on to produce several musical and dance video productions for some her songs, including ''Solipsist'' and ''Another Song About the Darkness.'' (''Choreography'' 2006).   \n\nThe album cover for her EP ''The Chemist Said It Would Be Alright But I\u2019ve Never Been The Same,'' was designed by [[outsider artist]] [[Wes Freed]]. ''Another Song About the Darkness'', from her album ''[[Choreography (Lauren Hoffman album)|Choreography]]'', is included on [[The Sound the Hare Heard]] album. A number of Hoffman's songs were played in the groundbreaking LGBT series [[South of Nowhere]], including ''Ghost You Know'', ''Magic Stick'', ''Hope You Don't Mind'', ''Reasons to Fall'' and ''Broken''. Her song ''Rock Star'' appears on the soundtrack of the 1998 motion picture, ''[[Palmetto (film)|Palmetto]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.laurenhoffman.com laurenhoffman.com]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoffman, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American folk singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n", "name_user": "Anon-Nyctophilia", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauren_Hoffman"}
{"title_page": "1911 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "The 1911 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was the second full organised club season in Auckland following the [[1910 Auckland Rugby League season]]. [[City Rovers]] won the title again after winning it in the competitions inaugural year.\n\n{{s-start}}\n        {{s-bef|before=[[1910 Auckland Rugby League season|1910]]}}\n        {{s-ttl|title=3rd [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n        |years=\t1911}}\n        {{s-aft|after=[[1912 Auckland Rugby League season|1912]]}}\n        {{end}}\n{{TOC right}}\n\nThe club season commenced on 20 May, with the start of the competition for the Myers Cup. [[City Rovers]] were crowned champions after defeating [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] in the final 36-15 which was required due to both teams being within 2 points of each other as the competition entered its closing stages. The competition at the time and for decades to come often did not complete full round robins. When a team had an unassailable lead over their nearest rivals the competition was often concluded at that point. Ponsonby and City had already met twice during the season but rather than conclude the round robin with round 10. In round 10 Ponsonby would have had a bye and City would likely have gained an easy win over wooden spooners, Eden Ramblers so the Auckland Rugby League decided to have the two top teams play off for the title a week early rather than prolong the competition.\n\nThe City side featured [[Albert Asher]], [[Alex Stanaway]], [[Jim Rukutai]], and [[Bob Mitchell (rugby league)|Bob Mitchell]], while Ponsonby had [[Charlie Savory]], [[Charles Dunning (rugby)|Charles Dunning]] and [[Arthur Carlaw]].\n\n===Venues===\nUnlike in 1910 when only two venues were used, there were 5 venues used. They were [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]], Takapuna Racecourse, 'Avondale', [[Auckland Domain]], and [[Eden Park]] (which was the venue for the club final between [[City Rovers]] and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]].\n\n===Eden Ramblers Formed===\nThe senior competition saw the addition of the Eden Ramblers who had been formed in April. A meeting was held at the Avondale Public Hall on Wednesday 26 April with Mr [[John Bollard (politician)|John Bollard, MP]] presiding over it. He was elected president and chairman, and the name Eden Ramblers was chosen along with the colours or green and gold. The following officers were selected: Hon Secretary, Mr B Boone; Management Committee, W. A. Cummings, J Eddoes, W Fairweather, M Morrow, and J Denyer. The membership was close to 50 and they were to begin their training for the season ahead on 29 April with a join practice with Ponsonby at Victoria Park.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Eden Ramblers Club\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVIII| issue=14666\n| date = 1911-04-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19110428.2.10\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n\n===Representative Season===\nIt featured a representative program in August and September where [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] played eight matches including two against the New Zealand side. They won seven and lost one. Their first match saw them lose to [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] however they rattled off consecutive wins against New Zealand (6 weeks later), [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington]], Lower Waikato, [[Hawke's Bay rugby league team|Hawke's Bay]], Nelson, [[Taranaki rugby league team|Taranaki]], and Hawke's Bay M\u0101ori.\n\n==Myers Cup (First Grade Championship)==\nEighteen regular season matches were played before the final on 16 September where [[City Rovers]] defeated [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] 36 to 15 to retain the title which they had won in 1910.\n\n===Final Standings===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|8||7||0||1||164||70||'''14'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|9||7||0||2||205||117||'''14'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions]]\n|7||3||0||4||80||68||'''6'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|7||1||0||6||51||138||'''2'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Eden Ramblers]]\n|7||1||0||6||42||149||'''2'''\n|-\n|}\nThe second round did not feature the final round of matches hence [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]] playing an extra match (when they were due to have a bye), while the table also includes the final played between [[City Rovers|City]] and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]].\n\n===Results===\n======Round 1======\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 20 May\n| time =\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 19\u20133\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Ponsonby v Newton\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLII| issue=120\n| date = 1911-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19110522.2.65\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| away = Newton\n| try1 = [[Charlie Savory]], S Cole, C Dillamore, Syd Riley 2\n| con1 = S Cole 2\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Sainsbury\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria park\n| attendance =\n| referee = Jaggs\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 20 May\n| time =\n| home = City\n| score = 13\u20133\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title =City v North Shore\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLII| issue=120\n| date = 1911-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19110522.2.65\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| away = North Shore\n| try1 = William Moeki, [[Jim Rukutai]]\n| con1 = [[Alex Stanaway]] 2\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Haddon\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance =\n| referee = W Pitts\n}}\n\n======Round 2======\n{{rugbybox collapsib