d===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 29 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 11\u20133\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand v Auckland\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLII| issue=180\n| date = 1911-07-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19110731.2.97\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| away = New Zealand\n| try1 = J Kay, [[Arthur Carlaw]], [[Stan Walters (rugby league)|Stan Walters]]\n| con1 = [[Albert Asher]]\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Ernie Buckland]]\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Takapuna Racecourse\n| attendance =\n| referee = Bob Oliphant\n}}\n\n===Auckland v Wellington (Northern Union Cup)===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 5 Aug\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 16\u20138\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title =First Challenge Match/Wellington v Auckland\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLII| issue=186\n| date = 1911-08-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19110807.2.75\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| away = Wellington\n| try1 = J Kay 2, [[Albert Asher]], Jim Bennett\n| con1 = [[Frank Morse (rugby league)|Frank Morse]]\n| pen1 = [[Frank Morse (rugby league)|Frank Morse]]\n| try2 = [[Bob Mitchell (rugby league)|Bob Mitchell]] 2\n| con2 = A Seeling\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 5000\n| referee = Cunningham\n}}\n\n===Auckland v Lower Waikato===\nJ Kay had the distinction of playing for Auckland one week, and then turning out against them the following week for Waikato. Occasionally players from the Waikato and Bay of Plenty regions would represent Auckland. Kay played 3 matches for Auckland in this season. The Auckland Star credited a conversion to Jim Griffen while the New Zealand Herald reported that [[Charles Dunning]] kicked all 3 goals. As the Auckland Star's match report was more detailed that is the record reported below.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 12 August\n| time =\n| home = Lower Waikato\n| score = 22\u201336\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland v Lower Waikato\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLII| issue=192\n| date = 1911-08-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19110814.2.64\n| accessdate = 2019-12-15}}</ref>\n| away = Auckland\n| try1 = J Kay 2, F Hall, R Gleeson\n| con1 = [[Reg Sprague]] 3\n| pen1 = [[Reg Sprague]]\n| drop1 = Hall\n| try2 = E Robinson, [[Bob Mitchell (rugby league)|Bob Mitchell]], Joe Bennett 4, [[Arthur Carlaw]], [[George Seagar]], [[Alfred Jackson (rugby league)|Alfred Jackson]] 2\n| con2 = [[Charles Dunning]] 2, [[Jim Griffen]]\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Frankton, Hamilton\n| attendance = 400\n| referee = Cunningham\n}}\n\n===Auckland v Hawke\u2019s Bay (Northern Union Cup)===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 19 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 17\u201313\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Retains the Cup/Hawke\u2019s Bay Beaten/An Exciting Contest\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVIII| issue=14764\n| date = 1911-08-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19110821.2.121.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-15}}</ref>\n| away = Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| try1 = [[Arthur Carlaw]], [[George Seagar]] 2, [[Jim Griffen]], [[Alf Chorley]]\n| con1 = [[Charles Dunning]]\n| pen1 = [[Charles Dunning]]\n| try2 = J Johnstone, G Jackson, G Frater\n| con2 = G Jackson\n| pen2 =\n| drop2 = G Jackson\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 3000\n| referee = W Jaggs\n}}\n\n===Auckland v Nelson (Northern Union Cup)===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 26 August\n| time =\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 36\u201312\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland Win Again/Victory Over Nelson\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVIII| issue=147680\n| date = 1911-08-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19110828.2.126.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-15}}</ref>\n| away = Nelson\n| try1 = [[Frank Morse (rugby league)|Frank Morse]], [[Jim Rukutai]] 3, [[Reg Sprague]], [[Jim Griffen]] 2, [[Harry Fricker]], George Harrison, [[Stan Walters (rugby league)|Stan Walters]]\n| con1 = [[Charles Dunning]] 3\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Cederman 2\n| con2 = Cederman 2\n| pen2 = [[Dave Mason (rugby league)|Dave Mason]]\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 5000\n| referee = McCarthy\n}}\n\n===Auckland v Taranaki (Northern Union Cup)===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 2 September\n| time =\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 26\u201315\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Interprovincial Cup/Auckland Beats Taranaki/A Record Attendance\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVIII| issue=147686\n| date = 1911-09-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19110904.2.147.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-15}}</ref>\n| away = Taranaki\n| try1 = [[Albert Asher]] 2, [[Jim Rukutai]], [[Harry Fricker]] 2, [[Bob Mitchell (rugby league)|Bob Mitchell]]\n| con1 = [[Charles Dunning]] 4\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = P Kyle, C Moir, Dan Twohill\n| con2 = [[Arthur Hardgrave]] 3\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 6000\n| referee = Matt Hooper\n}}\n\n===Auckland v Hawke\u2019s Bay M\u0101ori===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 9 September\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 22\u201310\n| report =<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hawke\u2019s Bay Natives v Auckland\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLII| issue=216\n| date = 1911-09-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19110911.2.74\n| accessdate = 2019-12-15}}</ref>\n| away = Hawke\u2019s Bay M\u0101ori\n| try1 = Joe Bennett 2, G Hunt, [[Jim Griffen]], [[Albert Asher]], C Linkhorn\n| con1 = [[Charles Dunning]] 2\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = W Paewai, Hopi Kani\n| con2 = W Hiha\n| pen2 = W Hiha\n| stadium = Takapuna Racecourse\n| attendance = 500\n| referee = Cunningham\n}}\n\n===Auckland Representative Matches Played and Scorers===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Rank!!Name!!Club!!Play!!Tries!!Con!!Pen!!Mark!!Points\n|-\n|1||Joe Bennett||Newton Rangers||7||9||-||-||-||27\n|-\n|2||[[Charles Dunning]]||Ponsonby United||6||-||12||1||-||26\n|-\n|3||[[Jim Griffen]]||North Shore Albions||8||4||1||-||-||14\n|-\n|3||[[Albert Asher]]||City Rovers||6||4||1||-||-||14\n|-\n|5||[[Harry Fricker]]||Ponsonby United||6||4||-||-||-||12\n|-\n|5||[[Jim Rukutai]]||Manukau Rovers||6||4||-||-||-||12\n|-\n|7||[[Arthur Carlaw]]||Ponsonby United||6||3||-||-||-||9\n|-\n|7||J Kay||Komakorau (Ngaruawahia Comp.)||3||3||-||-||-||9\n|-\n|9||[[Frank Morse (rugby league)|Frank Morse]]||City Rovers||4||1||1||1||-||7\n|-\n|9||[[George Seagar]]||North Shore Albions||3||1||2||-||-||7\n|-\n|11||[[Alfred Jackson (rugby league)|Alfred Jackson]]||North Shore Albions||8||2||-||-||-||6\n|-\n|11||[[Bob Mitchell (rugby league)|Bob Mitchell]]||City Rovers||5||2||-||-||-||6\n|-\n|11||George Harrison||North Shore Albions||2||2||-||-||-||6\n|-\n|11||[[Stan Walters (rugby league)|Stan Walters]]||North Shore Albions||2||2||-||-||-||6\n|-\n|15||[[Alf Chorley]]||Ponsonby United||3||1||-||-||-||3\n|-\n|15||E Robinson||City Rovers||6||1||-||-||-||3\n|-\n|15||C Linkhorn||Newton Rangers||2||1||-||-||-||3\n|-\n|15||[[Reg Sprague]]||Lower Waikato||1||1||-||-||-||3\n|-\n|15||George Hunt||City Rovers||1||1||-||-||-||3\n|-\n|20||S Cole||Ponsonby United||1||-||1||-||-||2\n|-\n|21||Harry Childs||City Rovers||6||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||C Dillamore||Ponsonby United||2||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||[[Don Kenealy]]||Eden Ramblers||2||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||[[Stan Weston]]||North Shore Albions||1||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||S Houghton||Ponsonby United||1||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||J Cummings||Eden Ramblers||1||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||J O\u2019Sullivan||City Rovers||1||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||[[Ernie Asher]]||City Rovers||1||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||[[Ronald MacDonald (rugby league)|Ronald MacDonald]]||North Shore Albions||1||-||-||-||-||-\n|-\n|21||Roy Denize||City Rovers||1||-||-||-||-||-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:1911 in New Zealand rugby league|Auckland Rugby League]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1911_Auckland_Rugby_League_season"}
{"title_page": "Shaddap You Face", "text_new": "{{short description|1980 single by Joe Dolce}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Shaddap You Face\n| cover      = Joe Dolce_-_SYF.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Joe Dolce|Joe Dolce Music Theatre]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Ain't in No Hurry\n| released   = 1980 (International)<br/>\nApril 1981 (U.S.)\n| format     = [[Vinyl record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = 1980\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Comedy music|comedy]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Full Moon Records]]<br/>[[Epic Records]] (UK)<ref name=\"500 Number One Hits\"/>\n| writer     = Joe Dolce<ref name=\"500 Number One Hits\">{{cite book\n| first= Jo\n| last= Rice\n| year= 1982\n| title= The Guinness Book of 500 Number One Hits\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Guinness Superlatives Ltd \n| location= Enfield, Middlesex\n| page= 212\n| isbn= 0-85112-250-7}}</ref>\n| producer   = Joe Dolce and Ian McKenzie<ref name=\"500 Number One Hits\"/>\n| chronology = [[Joe Dolce]]\n| prev_title = Boat People\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = If You Want to Be Happy\n| next_year  = 1981\n}}\n\"'''Shaddap You Face'''\" is a song written and performed by [[Joe Dolce]] (released under the name Joe Dolce Music Theatre) about a fictitious rebellious [[Italy|Italian]] boy. Released in late 1980, it set a number of sales and longevity records. The song was financed by [[Mike_Brady_(musician)|Mike Brady]]. <ref>[https://iview.abc.net.au/show/classic-countdown/series/0/video/LE1601V005S00  \"Classic Countdown\", 1979 episode, ABC Television, 2017 *The reference comes right at the end of this one hour episode]</ref><ref> https://www.abc.net.au/classiccountdown \"Classic Countdown\", ABC Television, 2017, 1979 episode. This link may work for international audiences with no geoblocks placed on it</ref>\n\n==Sales and chart positions==\n\"Shaddap You Face\" went to number one for eight weeks on the Australia [[Kent Music Report]] in 1980.<ref name=\"kmr\">{{cite book|last=Kent|first=David|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|edition=Illustrated|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St Ives, N.S.W.|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref> It reached number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]] on 21 February 1981 and stayed there for three weeks until 14 March 1981\u2014keeping [[Ultravox (band)|Ultravox's]] single \"[[Vienna (Ultravox song)|Vienna]]\" out of the top spot for all the three weeks it was there.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| pages= 390\u20131}}</ref>  The song became the 8th biggest hit of 1981 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-charts.top-source.info/top-100-1981.shtml |title=Top 100 1981 \u2013 UK Music Charts |website=Uk-charts.top-source.info |date= |accessdate=2016-10-23}}</ref>\n\n\"Shaddap You Face\" was also number one in 11 other countries. There have been over 50 different foreign language cover versions, and hundreds more published informally on YouTube with new versions being recorded and uploaded every year. The original release sold over 6 million copies and was the most successful Australian-produced single in Australian music history for many years, with sales of over 450,000 copies. It was Australia's first triple platinum recording by the old count of 100,000 units equalling platinum status, which has since changed to 75,000 units, then 50,000, and finally 70,000 units.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nIn the US, the song peaked at number 53 in the summer of 1981 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], number 43 on the ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100,<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/80s_files/19810627.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404235302/http://50.6.195.142/archives/80s_files/19810627.html |archivedate=4 April 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> and number 24 on ''[[Record World]]''. However, it was regularly played on the [[Dr. Demento]] show to the point of being number six on the year-end Funny 25 that year. In Quebec, \"Shaddap You Face\" reached number one for twelve weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0326&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=d4aa1bc4o6s09iksf4q7vfcci2 |title=Item Display \u2013 RPM \u2013 Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\n[[Lou Monte]] released a cover of the song in 1981.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I-5EjG-6r9o Lou Monte, \"Shaddap You Face,\" YouTube]</ref> Other notable cover versions have been done by [[KRS-One]] (hip-hop),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wTtjzzeR-HY KRS One, \"Shaddap You Face,\" YouTube]</ref> [[EMF (band)|EMF]] (British),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BTNJP8BNlm8 EMF, \"Shaddap your face,\" YouTube]</ref> [[Andrew Sachs]] (Manuel, of ''Fawlty Towers''), Werner B\u00f6hm, alias: Gottlieb Wendehals (German, title: Mensch, \u00e4rger dich nicht),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cizOXtMNgio Gottlieb Wendehals, \"Mensch, \u00e4rger dich nicht,\" YouTube]</ref> Sheila (French, titled: Et Ne La Ram\u00e8ne Pas),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tLlPRfjusYc SHEILA, \"Et ne la ramene pas,\" YouTube]</ref> Dingetje (Dutch, titled: Houtochdiekop),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C5fbE0_YnTw Dingetje, \"Houtochdiekop,\" YouTube]</ref> De Strangers (muziekgroep (Dutch, titled: Agget Mor Fret),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wZ1za2gXuR8 De Strangers, \"Agget mor fret,\" YouTube]</ref> Volker Rosin und die Lollypops (German, titled: H\u00f6rst du nicht die Kuh - Muh!), [[Franco Franchi]] with the duo, Franco e Ciccio (Italian, title: Al\u00ec Al\u00ec Al\u00e8),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2LkUcas74gc Franco e Ciccio, \"Al\u00ec Al\u00ec Al\u00e8,\" YouTube]</ref> an Aboriginal language version by Gnarnyarrhe Waitairie, a Papua New Guinean version by The Breeze Band (title: \"Pasim Pes Bilong Yu\" \u2013 pidgin version),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CFeEF65QsM0 Papua New Guinea Breeze Band, \"Pasim Pes Bilong Yu,\" YouTube]</ref> and a spoken word interpretation by [[Samuel L. Jackson]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GsDQ93iguP8 Samuel L. Jackson, \"Shaddap You Face,\" YouTube]</ref>\n\nA Czech interpretation written by Zden\u011bk Borovec, \"J\u00e1 na br\u00e1chu blues\", performed by [[Helena Vondr\u00e1\u010dkov\u00e1]] and [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Korn]], was a hit in Czechoslovakia in 1981<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lpd0WsMOUQY Helena Vondr\u00e1\u010dkov\u00e1 & Ji\u0159\u00ed Korn - J\u00e1 na br\u00e1chu blues (ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed video)]</ref>.\n\nThe [[National Folk Festival (Australia)|National Folk Festival]] in [[Canberra]] featured 'The Inspired Shaddap You Face Contest' in April 2006.  Festival artists were invited to perform their interpretations of the classic song. The Cygnet Folk Festival in Tasmania featured the second 'Inspired Shaddap You Face Contest' in the following year. [[Joe Dolce]] was invited to be the MC at both events.\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1980\u20131981)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak <br> position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref name=\"kmr\"/>\n|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|1|artist=Joe Dolce Music Theatre|song=Shaddap You Face|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 June 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|1|artist=Joe Dolce Music Theatre|song=Shaddap You Face|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 June 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|2|chartid=0376|row