her=St Martin's Press |year=1991 |isbn=0-312-06429-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/lowlifeinhighhee00wood_0 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0201343}}\n* {{findagrave|7705081}}\n* [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Entity/Show/entity_id/859 Darling's page on La MaMa Archives Digital Collections]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darling, Candy}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lymphoma]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Forest Hills, Queens]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Massapequa Park, New York]]\n[[Category:People associated with The Factory]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n | name             = Candy Darling\n | image            = Candy Darling on her Deathbed.jpg\n | imagesize        =\n | caption          = \"Candy Darling on her Deathbed\" by [[Peter Hujar]]\n | birth_date       = {{Birth date|1944|11|24|mf=y}}{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n | birth_place      = [[Forest Hills, Queens, New York]], U.S.\n | death_date       = {{Death date and age|1974|03|21|1944|11|24|mf=y}}\n | death_place      = [[New York City]], U.S.\n | resting_place    = Cherry Valley Cemetery, [[Cherry Valley, New York]], U.S.\n | occupation       = Actress\n}}\n\n'''Candy Darling''' (November 24, 1944 \u2013 March 21, 1974) was an American transsexual actress, best known as a [[Warhol Superstar]] and [[LGBT]] icon.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Candy Darling: Memoirs of an Andy Warhol Superstar|last1=Darling|first1=Candy|date=2015|publisher=Open Road Media|isbn=978-1-4804-0775-6|location=|page=201}}</ref><ref name=\"pagesix.com\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Richard |title=New details about Candy Darling's difficult, short life |url=https://pagesix.com/2018/06/10/new-details-about-candy-darlings-difficult-short-life/ |website=Page Six |accessdate=11 June 2018|date=June 10, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Plaza |first1=Cristina |title=Candy Darling, el reverso de la primera figura transexual de la cultura pop |url=http://www.revistavanityfair.es/celebrities/articulos/candy-darling-primera-figura-transexual-musa-andy-warhol-david-bowie-lou-reed/24884 |website=Vanity Fair |accessdate=29 June 2018|date=July 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=GLAAD Media Reference Guide - Transgender |url=https://www.glaad.org/reference/transgender |website=GLAAD |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> She starred in [[Andy Warhol]]'s films ''[[Flesh (1968 film)|Flesh]]'' (1968) and ''[[Women in Revolt]]'' (1971), and was a muse of [[The Velvet Underground]].\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Early life ==\n<!-- Note to editors: [[MOS:GENDERID]] summarizes Wikipedia's current guidelines for writing about transgender individuals. -->\n\nCandy Darling was born in [[Forest Hills, Queens]], the child of Theresa Slattery, a bookkeeper at Manhattan's Jockey Club,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://poststar.com/lifestyles/announcements/obituaries/theresa-catherine-p-mclean/article_93fcef9a-9dd0-11e3-b2bc-0019bb2963f4.html|title=Theresa Catherine P. McLean|work=Glens Falls Post-Star|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en}}</ref> and James (\"Jim\") Slattery, who was described as a violent [[alcoholic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=f-UPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9YsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6350,1338889&dq=candy-darling+forest-hills|title=Darling Candy, where were you the night Jean harlow died?|last=Bell|first=Arthur|date=May 18, 1972|work=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=June 18, 2009|quote=}}</ref>\n\nDarling's early years were spent in [[Massapequa Park]], [[Long Island]], where she and her mother moved after the parents' divorce. She spent much of her childhood watching television and old [[Hollywood]] movies, from which she learned to impersonate her favorite actresses, such as [[Joan Bennett]] and [[Kim Novak]]. She had one half-brother, Warren Law II, from her mother's first marriage to Warren Law. Warren Law II left to serve in the [[United States Armed Forces|United States military]] and left Darling as the only child. Law would later deny his connection to Darling.\n\nIn a biography about Darling, Cynthia Carr reveals that Darling was \"relentlessly bullied\" in high school and dropped out at the age of 16 after a group of boys tried to lynch her.<ref name=\"pagesix.com\" />\n\nIn 1961, she signed up for a course at the DeVern School of Cosmetology in [[Baldwin, Nassau County, New York|Baldwin, Long Island]].<ref name=Moynihan>{{cite news |last=Moynihan |first=Colin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/25/arts/design/25cand.html |title=From the Archives, a Portrait of a Pop-Art Muse |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 24, 2009 |accessdate=November 8, 2010}}</ref> Darling later said that she \"learned about the mysteries of sex from a salesman in a local children's shoe store\" and finally revealed an inclination towards [[cross-dressing]] when her mother confronted her about local rumors, which described Darling as \"dressing as a girl\" and frequenting a local [[gay bar]] called The Hayloft. In response, Darling left the room and returned in feminine clothing. Darling's mother would later say that, \"I knew then... that I couldn't stop (Candy). Candy was just too beautiful and talented.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Gary |last=Comenas |url=http://www.warholstars.org/stars/candy.html |title=Candy Darling |work=Warholstars.org |accessdate=November 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110203013118/http://www.warholstars.org/stars/candy.html |archivedate=February 3, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter coming out publicly, Darling would take a short cab ride to the [[Long Island Rail Road]] station, avoiding the attention of neighbors she would receive by walking to the train. From there, she would take the train to [[Manhattan]], often sitting across from Long Island starlet [[Joey Heatherton]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In Manhattan, she would refer to her family home at 79 First Avenue in Massapequa Park as her \"country house\", and spent time in [[Greenwich Village]], meeting people through Seymour Levy on [[Bleecker Street]].\n\nDarling met Jeremiah Newton in the summer of 1966, when Newton was on his first trip to [[Greenwich Village]] from his home in [[Flushing, Queens]]. The two became friends and roommates, living together in [[Manhattan]] and [[Brooklyn]] until the time of Darling's death in 1974.<ref name=Moynihan />\n\nDarling first took the name Hope Slattery. According to [[Bob Colacello]], Darling took this name in 1963/1964 after she started going to gay bars in [[Manhattan]] and visiting a doctor on Fifth Avenue for [[Hormone replacement therapy (male-to-female)|hormone injections]]. [[Jackie Curtis]] said that Darling adopted the name from a well-known [[Off-Off-Broadway|Off Broadway]] actress named Hope Stansbury, with whom she lived for a few months in an apartment behind the [[Caffe Cino]]. [[Holly Woodlawn]] remembers that Darling's name evolved from Hope Dahl to Candy Dahl, then to Candy Cane. Jeremiah Newton said she took the name \"Candy\" out of a love for sweets. In her autobiography, Woodlawn recalled that Darling had adopted the name because a friend of hers called her \"darling\" so often that it stuck.\n\n== Warhol years ==\nBefore they met, in 1967, Darling saw [[Andy Warhol]] at The Tenth of Always, an after-hours club. Darling was with [[Jackie Curtis]], who invited Warhol to a play that she had written and directed, called ''Glamour, Glory and Gold'', starring Darling as \"Nona Noonan\" and a young [[Robert De Niro]], who played six parts in the play.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mafiasecretjudge.com/DeNiro.html |title=What is the Robert DeNiro Connection? |work=For Members Only: The Story of the Mob's Secret Judge |accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWarhol cast Darling in a short comedic scene in ''[[Flesh (1968 film)|Flesh]]'' (1968) with Jackie Curtis and [[Joe Dallesandro]]. After ''Flesh'', Darling was cast in a central role in ''[[Women in Revolt]]'' (1971).\n\n''Women in Revolt'' was first shown at the first [[Filmex|Los Angeles Filmex]] as ''Sex''. It was later shown as ''Andy Warhol's Women.''\n\nThe day after the celebrity preview, a group of women carrying protest signs demonstrated outside the cinema against the film, which they thought was anti-[[Feminist movement|women's liberation]]. When Darling heard about this, she said, \"Who do these dykes think they are anyway? Well, I just hope they all read [[Vincent Canby]]'s review in today's ''[[The New York Times|Times.]]'' He said I look like a cross between [[Kim Novak]] and [[Pat Nixon]]. It's true&nbsp;\u2013 I do have Pat Nixon's nose.\" <ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy terror : Andy Warhol close up|last=Bob|first=Colacello|isbn=978-0-8041-6986-8|edition= First Vintage books |location=New York|oclc=855581110|year = 2014}}</ref>\n\nDarling worked for a short time as a barmaid at [[Slugger Ann|Slugger Ann's]], the bar owned by Jackie Curtis's grandmother.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Palladini|first=Giulia|date=May 26, 2011|title=Queer Kinship in the New York Underground: On the 'Life and Legend' of Jackie Curtis|url=https://www.academia.edu/4021580|journal=Contemporary Theatre Review|volume=21|issue=2|pages=126\u2013153|publisher=Routledge|accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== After Warhol ==\nDarling went on to appear in other independent films, including ''[[Silent Night, Bloody Night]]'', [[Wynn Chamberlain]]'s ''Brand X,'' and a co-starring role in ''[[Some of My Best Friends Are...]]''<ref name=\"imdb\" /> She appeared in ''[[Klute]]'' with [[Jane Fonda]] and ''[[Lady Liberty (film)|Lady Liberty]]'' with [[Sophia Loren]]. In 1971, she went to [[Vienna]] to make two films with director [[Werner Schroeter]]:''The Death of Maria Malibran'', and another film that was never released. Darling's attempt at breaking into mainstream movies, by campaigning for the leading role in ''[[Myra Breckinridge (film)|Myra Breckinridge]]'' (1970), led to rejection and bitterness.\n\nHer theatre credits include two Jackie Curtis plays, ''Glamour, Glory and Gold'' (1967) and ''Vain Victory: The Vicissitudes of the Damned'' (1971). ''Vain Victory'' was directed by Curtis at [[La MaMa Experimental Theatre Club]] in May/June 1971, and featured many other performers from Warhol's [[Warhol Factory|Factory]], including Curtis, [[Ondine (actor)|Ondine]], [[Tally Brown]], [[Mario Montez]], [[Samuel Adams Green]], [[Mary Woronov]], [[Francesco Scavullo]], Jay Johnson (twin brother of [[Jed Johnson (designer)|Jed Johnson]]), [[Holly Woodlawn]], [[Steina and Woody Vasulka]], [[Eric Emerson]], and Warhol himself.<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/975 \"Production: ''Vain Victory, The Vicissitudes of the Damned'' (1971)\". Accessed April 4, 2018.]</ref>\n\nDarling was in the original 1972 production of [[Tennessee Williams]]' play ''[[Small Craft Warnings]]'', cast at Williams' request. She starred in the 1973 revival of ''The White Whore and the Bit Player'', a 1964 play by [[Tom Eyen]], at [[La MaMa Experimental Theatre Club]]. The production was bilingual, called ''The White Whore and the Bit Player/La Estrelle y La Monja'', and directed by [[Manuel Mart\u00edn Jr.|Manuel Martin Jr]]. Darling's character, a Hollywood actress known only as \"the Whore\", was based on [[Marilyn Monroe]]. She performed in the English version opposite [http://amerinda.org/talkingstick/1-4/coatlique.html Hortensia Colorado], and the Spanish version was performed by [[Magaly Alabau]] and Graciela Mas.<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/289 \"Production: ''The White Whore and the Bit Player/La Estrella y La Monja'' (1973a)\". Accessed April 4, 2018.]</ref> As a review of the play stated, \"With her teased platinum hair and practiced pouts, Miss Darling looks like her character and resolutely keeps her acting little-girl-lost. The role-playing aspect works to her advantage. She could, after all, be a male lunatic pretending to be the White Whore.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Mel|last=Gussow|title=Eyen's 'The White Whore and Bit Player' Arrives|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 6, 1973}}</ref>\n\n== Illness and death ==\nDarling died of [[lymphoma]] on March 21, 1974, aged 29, at the [[Columbus Hospital]] division of the Cabrini Health Care Center.<ref name=Moynihan/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/03/22/archives/candy-darling-dies-warhol-superstar.html |title=Candy Darling Dies; Warhol 'Superstar'|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 22, 1974|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref> In a letter written on her deathbed and intended for Warhol and his followers, Darling wrote, \"Unfortunately before my death I had no desire left for life&nbsp;... I am just so bored by everything. You might say bored to death. Did you know I couldn't last. I always knew it. I wish I could meet you all again.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/books/article/BOOKS-Candy-s-Fairy-Tale-Face-Diaries-2832156.php|title=Candy's Fairy-Tale 'Face'; Diaries Reveal Longing For Identity|last=Wiegand|first=David|date=July 28, 1997|work=SFGate.com|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHer funeral, held at the [[Frank E. Campbell Funeral Chapel]], was attended by huge crowds. [[Julie Newmar]] read the eulogy.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Lopez, Alfred J.|title=Postcolonial Whiteness: A Critical Reader on Race and Empire|year=2012|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-8372-5|page=64}}</ref> Darling's birth name was never spoken by the minister or any of the eulogizers. [[Faith Dane]] played a piano piece, and [[Gloria Swanson]] saluted Darling's coffin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/blogs/niteside/122294884.html|title=\"Beautiful Darling\" Candy, Born as James|last=Donovan|first=Janet|date=May 23, 2011|work=NBCWashington.com|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDarling was [[cremation|cremated]], and her ashes were interred by Jeremiah Newton in the Cherry Valley Cemetery in [[Cherry Valley, New York]], a village at the foot of the [[Catskill Mountains]].\n\n== Legacy ==\n\n=== 2010 documentary ===\nA feature-length documentary on Darling, titled ''[[Beautiful Darling]]'', premiered at the [[Berlin International Film Festival]] (or [[Berlinale]]) in February 2010. The documentary features archival film and video footage, photographs, personal papers, archival audio interviews with [[Tennessee Williams]], [[Valerie Solanas]], [[Jackie Curtis]] and Darling's mother, as well as contemporary interviews with [[Holly Woodlawn]], [[Fran Lebowitz]], [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]], [[Julie Newmar]], [[Peter Beard]], and [[Taylor Mead]]. [[Chlo\u00eb Sevigny]] narrates the film, voicing Darling's private diary entries and personal letters. The film was directed by James Rasin and produced by Jeremiah Newton and Elisabeth Bentley.<ref>{{Citation|title=Beautiful Darling|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0960730/|access-date=2018-10-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Portrayals ===\n\n==== Film ====\n* Darling was first portrayed on film by [[Stephen Dorff]] in ''[[I Shot Andy Warhol]]'' (1996).<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|id=0201343}}</ref>\n* Darling is portrayed by [[Willam Belli]] in the 2011 [[HBO]] film ''[[Cinema Verite]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\" />\n\n==== Stage ====\n* Darling was portrayed by [[Brian Charles Rooney]] in ''Pop!'', a musical written by Anna K. Jacobs and Maggie-Kate Coleman and directed by [[Mark Brokaw]] at [[Yale Repertory Theatre]] in November\u2013December 2009.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Bacalzo |url=http://www.theatermania.com/connecticut/news/10-2009/doug-kreeger-randy-harrison-leslie-kritzer-brian-c_22123.html|title=Doug Kreeger, Randy Harrison, Leslie Kritzer, Brian Charles Rooney, et al. Set for Yale Rep's Pop!|work=TheaterMania.com|date=October 15, 2009|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* Darling was portrayed by actor Vince Gatton in the off-Broadway production of David Johnston's play ''Candy and Dorothy'', for which Gatton received a [[Drama Desk Award|Drama Desk award]] nomination.<ref>{{cite web|authorlink1=Robert Simonson|first=Robert|last=Simonson|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/99343-The-Drowsy-Chaperone-Leads-2006-Drama-Desk-Nominations|title=''The Drowsy Chaperone'' Leads 2006 Drama Desk Nominations|work=Playbill.com|date=April 27, 2006|accessdate=July 30, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428075928/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/99343-The-Drowsy-Chaperone-Leads-2006-Drama-Desk-Nominations|archivedate=April 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Music ====\n* Darling and her friend Taffy are mentioned in the chorus of the 1967 [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] song \"[[Citadel (song)|Citadel]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Paytress|first1=Mark|title=Rolling Stones: Off the Record|date=2009|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-85712-113-4}}</ref>\n* Darling is the subject of the song \"[[Candy Says]]\", the opening track on [[The Velvet Underground]]'s [[The Velvet Underground (album)|self-titled album]] in 1969, sung by [[Doug Yule]].<ref>{{harvnb|DeCurtis|2017}}{{page needed|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n* The second verse of [[Lou Reed]]'s 1972 \"[[Walk on the Wild Side (Lou Reed song)|Walk on the Wild Side]]\" is devoted to Darling.<ref>{{harvnb|DeCurtis|2017|page=123}}</ref>\n\n==== Visual arts ====\n* [[Greer Lankton]] made a bust of Darling that was displayed at the 1995 [[Whitney Biennial]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Morton|first=Julia|title=Greer Lankton, A Memoir|work=artnet|publisher=Artnet Worldwide Corporation|date=January 26, 2007|url=http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/morton/morton1-26-07.asp|accessdate=March 13, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Hujar]]'s photo, \"Candy Darling on her Deathbed\", was used by [[Antony and the Johnsons]] for the cover of their 2005 [[Mercury Music Prize]]-winning album ''[[I Am a Bird Now]]''.<ref name=\"Credits\">[http://www.allmusic.com/album/i-am-a-bird-now-r727389/credits I Am a Bird Now \u2013 Credits], Allmusic.com; retrieved July 3, 2011.</ref>\n\n=== Namesakes ===\n* In 2009, ''C\u2606NDY'', which calls itself \"the first transversal style magazine\", debuted. It is named after Darling.<ref name=\"Tim Blanks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.style.com/culture/entertainment/2014/transgender-stars-candy-magazine-cover|title=Exclusive: The World's Biggest Transgender Stars Cover C\u2606NDY|author-link=Tim Blanks|first=Tim|last=Blanks|work=style.com}}</ref>\n* [[Byredo]] created a candle scent named after Darling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/spy/15th-anniversary/zac-posen/byredo-parfums-candles-%28candy-darling-scent%29|website=Vogue UK|title=Zac Posen \u2013 15 favourite things|accessdate=April 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412032501/http://www.vogue.co.uk/spy/15th-anniversary/zac-posen/byredo-parfums-candles-(candy-darling-scent)|archive-date=April 12, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Biopic ===\nIn January 2019, a [[biopic]] about Candy was announced. It will be written by Stephanie Kornick and executive produced by [[Zackary Drucker]]. The film is being produced by Christian D. Bruun, Katrina Wolfe, and Louis Spiegler.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/candy-darling-biopic-stephanie-kornick-zackary-drucker-andy-warhol-factor-lgbtq-representation-inclusion-1202544771/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 29, 2019|title='Transparent's Stephanie Kornick And Zackary Drucker Board Candy Darling Biopic|first=Dino-Ray|last=Ramos}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Filmography ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Flesh (1968 film)|Flesh]]''\n| Candy\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''Brand X''\n| Marlene D-Train\n|\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Lady Liberty (film)|La Mortadella]]''\n| Transvestite\n| Alternative title: ''Lady Liberty''\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Klute]]''\n| Discoth\u00e8que Patron\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Some of My Best Friends Are...]]''\n| Karen / Harry\n|\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Women in Revolt]]''\n| Candy\n|\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Lady Liberty (film)|Lady Liberty]]''\n| Transvestite\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Der Tod der Maria Malibran|fr|3=La Mort de Maria Malibran|lt=Der Tod der Maria Malibran}}''\n|\n| Directed by [[Werner Schroeter]]\n|-\n|1972\n|''[[Silent Night, Bloody Night]]''\n| Guest\n| (final film role)\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[An American Family]]''\n|Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The Cockettes (film)|The Cockettes]]''\n| Herself\n| Archive footage\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Superstar in a Housedress]]''\n| Herself\n| Archive footage\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Andy Warhol: A Documentary Film]]''\n| Herself\n| Archive footage\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Beautiful Darling]]''\n| Herself\n| Archive footage\n|}\n\n== References ==\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Works cited\n* {{cite book|last=DeCurtis|first=Anthony|title=Lou Reed: A Life|date=2017|publisher=Little, Brown|isbn=978-0-316-37654-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v1cRDgAAQBAJ|ref=harv}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |title=The Life and Death of Andy Warhol |first=Victor |last=Bockris |publisher=4th Estate |year=1998 |isbn=1-85702-805-8}}\n* {{cite book |title=Holy Terror: Andy Warhol close up |first=Bob |last=Colacello |publisher=Cooper Square |year=2000 |isbn=0-8154-1008-5}}\n* {{cite book |title=Man Enough to be a Woman |first=Jayne |last=County |authorlink=J